## Phase 0 — Context (run once at session start)

> I have a popup system in a SwiftUI app: a "sequencer" that defines an ordered
> set of popups and a coordinator (a Swift class) that, on triggers from the main
> coordinator, checks each popup's condition and presents the first/eligible one.
>
> I want to refactor it toward the architecture described in
> `POPUP_REFACTOR_PLAN.md` (rule-based popups, a single-winner engine, and a
> SwiftUI `@Observable` presenter).
>
> Important: the existing presentation conditions and the state they read are the
> source of truth. Find that logic in the current code and preserve it — do not
> assume where state comes from or how conditions are computed. The refactor
> changes structure, not behavior.
>
> Work in phases. Do NOT write or change code yet. For each phase, show me
> before/after diffs and STOP for my approval before proceeding. Confirm you
> understand.

## Discovery — Locate the popup system (awareness)

Run this **before** the audit. Its only job is to make the agent find every piece
of the existing popup system, so nothing gets missed and silently dropped.

> Discovery — Do NOT change anything. First, locate the entire popup system in
> this codebase so we're certain we have the full picture before refactoring.
>
> Search broadly, not just by the names I've used:
>
> - The sequencer type and the coordinator class that drives popups.
> - Every popup these manage, and their view types.
> - SwiftUI presentation sites: `.sheet`, `.fullScreenCover`, `.popover`,
>   `.alert`, `.confirmationDialog`, and any custom overlay presentation.
> - Anything matching terms like "popup", "sequence(r)", "coordinator",
>   "present", "modal", "onboarding", "prompt", "banner".
> - Any popups presented OUTSIDE the sequencer (one-off `.sheet`s elsewhere) —
>   flag these as "not currently managed; confirm whether they belong in scope".
>
> Produce a table: file path · symbol/type · what it presents · how it's
> triggered · whether it goes through the sequencer or is presented independently.
> Then explicitly state: "This is the complete set" or list what you're unsure
> about. STOP and wait for me to confirm the set is complete before auditing.

**Why this gate matters:** the correctness of the whole refactor depends on
converting _every_ popup. Confirming the full inventory here — including stray
popups presented outside the sequencer — is what prevents behavior from quietly
disappearing later.

## Phase 1 — Audit only, no changes

> Phase 0 — Audit. Using the confirmed inventory from Discovery, read the
> sequencer, the coordinator, and every popup in that set. Do not modify anything.
> Produce a short report covering:
>
> 1. Is the current behavior "pick one winner per trigger" or "queue multiple in
>    sequence"? Quote the lines that decide this.
> 2. List every popup, its trigger point(s), and its presentation condition.
> 3. Where does each condition read state from (UserDefaults, DB, remote config)?
> 4. Frequency capping: is "don't show again / cooldown" logic duplicated across
>    popups?
> 5. Concurrency: can two triggers race into a double-present? Is presentation on
>    the main actor?
> 6. How tightly is the decision logic coupled to the sequencer body (does adding
>    a popup require editing a central if/else or switch)?
>
> End with a proposed phase plan to reach the target architecture, ordered to keep
> each diff small. Then stop.

**Why this matters:** the audit settles whether "order + first condition that
meets" is winner-selection or queueing. Require quoted lines so it isn't a guess.

## Phase 2 — Scaffold the abstractions (additive only)

> Phase 1 — Add the new abstractions WITHOUT touching existing popups or wiring
> yet. Create, in new files:
>
> - `PopupID`, `PopupTrigger`, `PopupContext` — where `PopupContext` carries
>   exactly the state the existing conditions read (as found in the audit), and
>   nothing invented.
> - `protocol PopupRule { id; priority; func shouldPresent(_:) async -> Bool;
func makeView() -> AnyView }`
> - `PopupEngine` that returns the single highest-priority eligible rule for a
>   trigger.
> - ONLY IF the audit found repeated "already shown / cooldown" logic: a single
>   store to hold it, behind the project's existing StoredKey-style storage
>   abstraction (in-memory + real implementations). If no such logic exists,
>   skip this — do not introduce new state.
>
> The existing system must still compile and behave identically after this phase
> — these are unused additions. Show the diff and stop.

## Phase 3 — Migrate popups one at a time

> Phase 2 — Migrate ONE popup (start with the simplest) into a `PopupRule`
> conforming type. Move its existing condition into `shouldPresent` **verbatim** —
> same checks, same state sources, same order — and its view into `makeView`. If
> that popup has "already shown / cooldown" handling, relocate it into the shared
> store from Phase 1 without changing what it computes. Do not add, drop, or
> reinterpret any condition. Leave it registered in BOTH the old path and the new
> engine for now if needed, but mark the old path clearly. Show before/after diff
> for that one popup only, explicitly call out any behavior difference (there
> should be none), and stop.
>
> After I approve, repeat for the next popup. One popup per turn.

**Checkpoint:** after the first popup migrates, confirm winner-vs-queue matches
intent. If the old code queues but you want a single winner, that's a deliberate
behavior change — not something buried in a diff.

## Phase 4 — Swap in the engine + SwiftUI presenter

> Phase 3 — Replace the coordinator's decision logic with the engine, and replace
> imperative presentation with a SwiftUI `@Observable` presenter exposing
> `active: PopupRule?`, driven by `.sheet(item:)` or `.fullScreenCover(item:)` at
> the app's root. The main coordinator should now call
> `presenter.evaluate(trigger:)` at each trigger point instead of running
> conditions itself.
>
> Add a mutual-exclusion guard so overlapping triggers can't double-present, and
> ensure presentation runs on the main actor. Delete the old sequencer decision
> code only after the new path covers every popup. Show the full diff and stop.

## Phase 5 — Tests + cleanup

> Phase 4 — Write tests for: priority winner selection when multiple rules are
> eligible; the double-present guard under two near-simultaneous triggers; and
> per-trigger eligibility. If a cooldown/seen store exists, use its in-memory
> implementation to test suppression too. Then remove dead code from the old path
> and list anything left coupled to the sequencer. Show the diff and stop.

